This paper discusses algorithmic decisions and their potential discrimination against protected groups, which falls under the category of computational social science (cs.CY). The paper also mentions fairness and transparency in ranking algorithms, which are topics commonly discussed in the fields of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The mention of criminal risk assessment suggests a potential connection to computer security and cryptography (cs.CR), while the use of financial services data may relate to social and information networks (cs.SI).
